Spatial subset

Check current projection

ext(rast_stack)
## SpatExtent : -3950000, 3950000, -3950000, 4350000 (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)

The spatial extent is in a projected coordinate system, and the values are in meters. The values (-3950000, 3950000, -3950000, 4350000) are pseudo-Mercator projection often used for global datasets.

My subset extent is in degrees (longitude and latitude), so I reprojected the raster stack to WGS 84 geographic coordinate system:

# Define your spatial extent 
subset_extent <- c(115, 245, -80, -40)

# Set the target CRS - longitudes range from -180 to +180
target_crs <- "+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84"

# Reproject and rotate each raster in the stack individually
rast_stack_rotated <- lapply(rast_stack, function(r) terra::rotate(terra::project(r, target_crs),left=FALSE))

# Combine the list of reprojected and rotated raster layers into a raster stack
rast_stack_rotated <- terra::rast(rast_stack_rotated)

## Subset the rotated and shifted raster stack
rast_subset <- terra::crop(rast_stack_rotated, subset_extent)
ext(rast_stack_rotated)
## SpatExtent : -0.193340494092354, 359.806659505908, -89.8912976566242, -39.2299412121644 (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
ext(rast_subset)
## SpatExtent : 115.037593984962, 244.962406015038, -79.8363719500902, -40.003397035744 (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)

Explore a few plots of uds, which has three layers defining area of most use for 25,50 and 75% of time spent in grid cells while foraging. The methodology to calculate individual utilisation distributions (UDi, a measure of the total area used by an individual seal) followed the same methodology as: Harcourt, R., Hindell, M. A., McMahon, C. R., Goetz, K. T., Charrassin, J.-B., Heerah, K., . . . Pinkerton, M. H. (2021). Regional variation in winter foraging strategies by Weddell Seals in eastern Antarctica and the Ross Sea. Frontiers in Marine Science, Volume 8 - 2021. doi:10.3389/fmars.2021.720335

The shapes are split to distinguish 50 from 75% spatial extent. However, to use 50% as a full spatial cover of the area, we need to also include the 75% area in our subset. So combining these two into one shapefile:

plot(uds_50[,1 ])

plot(uds_75[,1 ])

This is done as per below:

SO_uds_50 <-  crop(rast_subset, vect(uds_50))
SO_uds_50 <- mask(SO_uds_50,vect(uds_50))

SO_uds_75 <-  crop(rast_subset, vect(uds_75))
SO_uds_75 <- mask(SO_uds_75,vect(uds_75))

SIC >15

Sea Ice Concentrations need to be greater that 15% to be considered covering, so this code calculates what the percentage is of grid cells within the subset that exceed 15% SIC each year. The data is considered only for only the relevant months (March to October) when female seals are out on their post-moult foraging trip.

# Define the months of interest
months_of_interest <- c(3:10)

# Initialize variables
num_layers <- nlyr(ICE_subset)
coverage_percentages <- numeric(num_layers)

# Calculate coverage for each layer
for (i in 1:num_layers) {
  layer <- ICE_subset[[i]]
  
  # Create a binary mask indicating whether each grid cell has SIC > 15
  mask <- ifelse(values(layer) > 15, 1, 0)
  
  # Calculate the percentage of cells with SIC > 15, excluding NAs
  non_zero_count <- sum(mask, na.rm = TRUE)
  total_cells <- sum(!is.na(values(layer)))
  
  coverage_percentages[i] <- if (total_cells > 0) {
    100 * non_zero_count / total_cells
  } else {
    NA
  }
}

# Create a data frame with coverage percentages and dates
dates <- seq(as.Date("1980-01-01"), by = "months", length.out = num_layers)
df <- data.frame(Date = dates, Coverage = coverage_percentages)

# Filter the data for the months of interest
df$Month <- format(df$Date, "%m")
df$Year <- format(df$Date, "%Y")
df_filtered <- df[df$Month %in% sprintf("%02d", months_of_interest), ]

# Calculate the annual summary (e.g., mean coverage)
annual_summary <- aggregate(Coverage ~ Year, data = df_filtered, FUN = mean, na.rm = TRUE)

Quick plot to explore values

annual_summary$Year <- as.numeric(annual_summary$Year)

# Create a line plot
ggplot(annual_summary, aes(x = Year, y = Coverage)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue") +
  geom_point(color = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Annual Sea Ice Concentration Coverage (March - October)",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Coverage Percentage") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "grey", linetype = "dashed"))

## Anomaly

Convert percentages to an anomaly value by subtracting each from the total mean of the whole timeseries:

annual_summary$Anomaly <- annual_summary$Coverage - (sum(annual_summary$Coverage)/nrow(annual_summary) )

Plot anomalies

# Create a line plot
ggplot(annual_summary, aes(x = Year, y = Anomaly)) +
  geom_line(color = "black") +
  geom_point(color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Annual Sea Ice Concentration Coverage (March - October)",
       x = "Year",
       y = "SIC Anomaly") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "grey", linetype = "dashed"))

Make publication Figure:

add_y_break <- function(plot, yval) {
  p2 <- ggplot_build(plot)
  breaks <- p2$layout$panel_params[[1]]$y$breaks
  breaks <- breaks[!is.na(breaks)]
  plot +
    geom_hline(yintercept = yval, color = "grey") +
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = sort(c(yval, breaks)))
}
# Base plot
p <- ggplot(annual_summary, aes(x = Year, y = Coverage)) +
  geom_segment(aes(x = Year, xend = Year, y = Coverage, yend = 37.47, color = Anomaly > 0), size = 1) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("TRUE" = "#FFCC66", "FALSE" = "#00CC99")) +
  geom_line(color = "black") +
  geom_point(color = "black") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 37.47, color = "grey") +
  # Add label on the right side of the horizontal line
  labs(x = "",
       y = "% sea ice cover") +
  guides(color = "none") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "grey", linetype = "dashed"),
        axis.title.y = element_text(margin = margin(r = 10, t=10)))  # Adjust the margin as needed
## Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
##  Please use `linewidth` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.

## generated.
# Add labeled horizontal line at the average
p <- add_y_break(p, 37.47)

# Print the final plot
print(p)
